dependence of airÔ¨āow on the sea state comes from the observed dependence of the drag coeÔ¨Écient on the wave age. Measurements by, for example, Donelan (1982) and Smith et al (1992) have conÔ¨Ārmed the dependence of the drag coeÔ¨Écient on wave age. For a Ô¨Āxed wind speed at 10 m height Donelan found that, depending on the sea state, the drag coeÔ¨Écient may vary by a factor of two.
The theory of the interaction of wind and waves was elaborated by Fabrikant (1976) and Janssen (1982). The so-called quasi-linear theory of windwave generation keeps track of the slow evolution of the sea state and its eÔ¨Äects on the wind proÔ¨Āle. At each particular time the wave growth follows from Miles‚Äô theory. It turns out that quasi-linear theory permits an explanation of the observed dependence of the airÔ¨āow on the sea state.
The structure of this Chapter is as follows. First, we discuss the linear, quasi-laminar theory of wind-wave generation, based on Miles‚Äô shear Ô¨āow mechanism. Basically, this mechanism of the generation of waves by wind is a resonant interaction of the gravity waves with a plane parallel Ô¨āow. Resonance occurs at a critical height zc which follows from U (zc) = c(k). Here, U is the air velocity and c(k) the phase velocity of a wave with wavenumber k. Only those waves grow for which the curvature of the velocity proÔ¨Āle at the critical height is negative. Results of this theory are compared with available Ô¨Āeld and laboratory measurements.
After the discussion of the quasi-laminar approach a brief account of the eÔ¨Äects of turbulence is given. First, a brief discussion of the eÔ¨Äects of smallscale turbulence is given, followed by the Belcher and Hunt criticism why mixing length modelling is not appropriate in rapidly varying circumstances such as occur for airÔ¨āow over growing wind-waves. The approach of Belcher and Hunt allows for a determination of the range of validity of Miles‚Äô theory. Depending on the assumption regarding how rapid eddies transfer momentum, Miles‚Äô approach may be justiÔ¨Āed for typical ocean conditions. Second, a

