treatment of the eÔ¨Äects of gusts on wave growth is presented. This treatment assumes that the period of the waves is shorter than a relevant time scale of gustiness. Then, if the probability distribution of the Ô¨āuctuations in stress due to the gusts is known, an appropriate averaging of the Miles‚Äô results will immediately give the eÔ¨Äect of gusts on wave growth. In particular, the growth rate of low-frequency waves will be aÔ¨Äected to a considerable extent.
Next, we proceed with a discussion of the quasi-linear theory of windwave generation, which culminates in a derivation of the relation between drag coeÔ¨Écient and the sea state. This relation is then validated against existing Ô¨Āeld data.

